04927nam a22007215i 9781501720468DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017204687 a10.7591/97815017204682doi  a(DE-B1597)527435  a(OCoLC)1105907149  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ1190b.A4 2000 7aLIT0030002bisacsh04a305.42/012211 aAlaimo, Stacy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUndomesticated Ground :bRecasting Nature as Feminist Space /cStacy Alaimo. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b6 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Feminist Theory's Flight from Nature -- tPart I. Feminist Landscapes -- tChapter 1. Feminism at the Border: Nature, Indians, and Colonial Space -- tChapter 2. Darwinian Landscapes: Hybrid Spaces and the Evolution of Woman in Sarah Orne Jewett and Mary Wilkins Freeman -- tChapter 3. The Undomesticated Nature of Feminism: Mary Austin and the Progressive Women Conservationists -- tPart II. Nature as Political Space -- tChapter 4. Emma Goldman's Mother Earth and the Nature of the Left -- tChapter 5. Reproduction as a Natural Disaster -- tPart III. Feminism, Postmodernism, Environmentalism -- tChapter 6. Playing Nature: Postmodern Natures in Contemporary Feminist Fiction -- tChapter 7. Cyborgs, Whale Tails, and the Domestication of Environmentalism -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom "Mother Earth" to "Mother Nature," women have for centuries been associated with nature. Feminists, troubled by the way in which such representations show women controlled by powerful natural forces and confined to domestic space, have sought to distance themselves from nature. In Undomesticated Ground, Stacy Alaimo issues a bold call to reclaim nature as feminist space. Her analysis of a remarkable range of feminist writings—as well as of popular journalism, visual arts, television, and film—powerfully demonstrates that nature has been and continues to be an essential concept for feminist theory and practice.Alaimo urges feminist theorists to rethink the concept of nature by probing the vastly different meanings that it carries. She discusses its significance for Americans engaged in social and political struggles from, for example, the "Indian Wars" of the early nineteenth century, to the birth control movement in the 1920s, to contemporary battles against racism and heterosexism. Reading works by Catherine Sedgwick, Mary Austin, Emma Goldman, Nella Larson, Donna Haraway, Toni Morrison, and others, Alaimo finds that some of these writers strategically invoke nature for feminist purposes while others cast nature as a postmodern agent of resistance in the service of both environmentalism and the women's movement.By examining the importance of nature within literary and political texts, this book greatly expands the parameters of the nature writing genre and establishes nature as a crucial site for the cultural work of feminism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEcofeminism. 0aFeminist theory. 0aNature in literature. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 4aGender Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aNature Guides & Natural History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172046840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501720468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501720468.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2